{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17564424","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17564424"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T23:13:58+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T23:13:58+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16977"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"16977","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/16977"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.08,0.06,0.61,0.12,0.13]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9667"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"68110"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"9667","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/9667"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16977"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"53568"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"23"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"2166"},{"type":"tags","id":"4671"},{"type":"tags","id":"4972"},{"type":"tags","id":"4980"},{"type":"tags","id":"4985"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"11153"},{"type":"tags","id":"11634"},{"type":"tags","id":"11640"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"},{"type":"tags","id":"11993"},{"type":"tags","id":"12802"},{"type":"tags","id":"12807"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"22794"},{"type":"contributions","id":"43681"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"68110","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/68110"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 26-year-old woman presents to the antenatal clinic at 16 weeks gestation in her first pregnancy. She was born in Somalia and moved to Australia five years ago. She has type 3 female genital mutilation which was performed in childhood. She has no other medical history and takes only pregnancy multivitamins. On examination, she appears well with vital signs within normal limits. Abdominal examination reveals a gravid uterus consistent with dates.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate management option to discuss with this patient?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Delayed infibulation","Exinfibulation","Deinfibulation","Reinfibulation","Infibulation"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient has type 3 female genital mutilation (FGM), also known as infibulation, which involves the narrowing of the vaginal opening through creation of a covering seal. This can cause significant complications during pregnancy and childbirth if not addressed.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDeinfibulation\u003C/strong\u003E is the surgical procedure to open up the sealed vaginal opening and should be offered during pregnancy, ideally in the second trimester. This timing allows healing before delivery and enables vaginal examinations during pregnancy. The procedure involves dividing the midline scar tissue that covers the vaginal opening and urethral meatus.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDelayed infibulation\u003C/strong\u003E is not a recognised medical procedure and would be inappropriate and potentially harmful in this context.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EExinfibulation\u003C/strong\u003E is not a correct medical term - the proper term is deinfibulation for the reversal of FGM type 3.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EReinfibulation\u003C/strong\u003E refers to re-closing the vaginal opening after childbirth in women with FGM. This practice is illegal in many countries and is not recommended due to associated health risks.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EInfibulation\u003C/strong\u003E refers to the original procedure of creating the covering seal and is a form of FGM. It is illegal in most countries and performing it would be unethical and criminal.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EWomen with FGM should receive culturally sensitive care from healthcare providers who understand the physical and psychological implications of FGM. Counselling about deinfibulation should include discussion of the procedure, timing, and benefits for both pregnancy care and future health.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Deinfibulation should be offered to women with type 3 female genital mutilation (FGM) during pregnancy, ideally in the second trimester.","Type 3 FGM involves narrowing of the vaginal opening through creation of a covering seal, with or without removal of the clitoris.","Early deinfibulation reduces complications during labour and delivery, and allows for easier antenatal examinations."],"references":["Royal Australian and New Zealand College of Obstetricians and Gynaecologists (RANZCOG). Female genital mutilation (FGM) [Internet]. Melbourne: RANZCOG; 2023 [cited 2024 Jun 23]. Available from: https://ranzcog.edu.au/wp-content/uploads/Female-Genital-Mutilation.pdf"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"53568"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16977"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"53568","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/53568"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-09T10:05:42+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-09T10:06:44+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9667"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"68110"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"23","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/23"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udd30","name":"Obstetrics","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"